Datemaki

Ingredients (Serves 2)

Base
	•	4 large eggs
	•	80 g (3 oz) hanpen (white fish cake), torn into pieces

Liquid Seasoning
	•	80 ml (1/3 cup) dashi
	•	20 g (1½ tbsp) sugar
	•	10 ml (2 tsp) soy sauce

Pan Prep
	•	5 ml (1 tsp) neutral oil

Allergen-friendly options:
	•	Replace hanpen with firm tofu for a fish-free version
	•	Replace soy sauce with coconut aminos for soy-free

⸻

Method
	1.	Blend Base
Blend eggs, hanpen, and dashi until completely smooth and silky.
	2.	Strain
Pass mixture through a fine-mesh sieve to remove air bubbles and any remaining solids.
	3.	Season
Gently whisk in sugar and soy sauce until fully dissolved, avoiding excess air.
	4.	Heat Pan
Lightly oil a rectangular tamagoyaki pan (or small nonstick skillet). Heat over medium-low until just warm; oil should not smoke.
	5.	Cook Gently
Pour in egg mixture. Cover and cook slowly, lifting edges every 30 seconds to let uncooked egg flow underneath. Cook until just set but still pliable and custard-like.
	6.	Roll
Invert omelette onto a bamboo mat. Roll tightly into a log, using the mat to create ridges.
	7.	Set Shape
Keep wrapped and rest 15 minutes to set. Unwrap and allow to cool slightly before slicing.

⸻

Optional Refinements
	•	Add 5 g finely crushed bonito flakes to the blended mixture for deeper umami
	•	Bake at 160°C (320°F) until just set, then roll while hot for a traditional oven-style version
	•	Garnish sliced datemaki with yuzu zest for a bright aromatic finish